.\" Man page for types and compile-time configuration
.TH HIVE_TYPES 3 "January 2026" "Hive 1.0" "Actor Runtime Manual"
.SH NAME
hive_types, hive_status, hive_message, actor_config \- runtime types and constants
.SH SYNOPSIS
.nf
.B #include <hive_types.h>
.B #include <hive_static_config.h>
.fi
.SH DESCRIPTION
This manual describes the fundamental types, constants, and compile-time
configuration for the actor runtime.
.SS Handles
.TP
.B actor_id
Opaque 32-bit handle identifying an actor.
.TP
.B ACTOR_ID_INVALID
Sentinel value (0) indicating an invalid or uninitialized actor ID.
.TP
.B bus_id
Opaque 32-bit handle identifying a bus (defined in
.IR <hive_bus.h> ).
.TP
.B BUS_ID_INVALID
Sentinel value (0) indicating an invalid bus ID (defined in
.IR <hive_bus.h> ).
.TP
.B timer_id
Opaque 32-bit handle identifying a timer (defined in
.IR <hive_timer.h> ).
.TP
.B TIMER_ID_INVALID
Sentinel value (0) indicating an invalid timer ID (defined in
.IR <hive_timer.h> ).
.SS Status Type
.PP
.nf
typedef struct {
    hive_error_code code;  /* Error code */
    const char    *msg;    /* String literal or NULL, never heap-allocated */
} hive_status;
.fi
.PP
All runtime functions return
.I hive_status
to indicate success or failure. The
.I msg
field provides a human-readable error description when non-NULL.
.SS Status Macros
.TP
.B HIVE_SUCCESS
Status value for successful operations.
.TP
.BI HIVE_SUCCEEDED( s )
True if status
.I s
indicates success.
.TP
.BI HIVE_FAILED( s )
True if status
.I s
indicates failure.
.TP
.BI HIVE_ERROR( code ", " msg )
Create a status with error code and message.
.TP
.BI HIVE_ERR_STR( s )
Extract error message from status, returning "unknown error" if NULL.
.SS Error Codes
.TP
.B HIVE_OK
Operation succeeded.
.TP
.B HIVE_ERR_NOMEM
Resource pool exhausted (actor table, mailbox pool, message pool, etc.).
.TP
.B HIVE_ERR_INVALID
Invalid argument, invalid handle, or operation not permitted in current context.
.TP
.B HIVE_ERR_TIMEOUT
Operation timed out.
.TP
.B HIVE_ERR_CLOSED
Target actor or resource is closed/dead.
.TP
.B HIVE_ERR_WOULDBLOCK
Non-blocking operation would block.
.TP
.B HIVE_ERR_IO
I/O error (network or file).
.SS Message Structure
.PP
.nf
typedef struct {
    actor_id       sender;  /* Sender actor ID */
    hive_msg_class class;   /* Message class */
    uint32_t       tag;     /* Message tag */
    size_t         len;     /* Payload length in bytes */
    const void    *data;    /* Payload pointer */
} hive_message;
.fi
.PP
The
.I data
pointer is valid until the next successful
.BR hive_ipc_recv ().
.SS Message Classes
.TP
.B HIVE_MSG_NOTIFY
Fire-and-forget notification (0).
.TP
.B HIVE_MSG_REQUEST
Request expecting reply (1).
.TP
.B HIVE_MSG_REPLY
Reply to a request (2).
.TP
.B HIVE_MSG_TIMER
Timer tick from runtime (3).
.TP
.B HIVE_MSG_EXIT
Actor death notification (4).
.TP
.B HIVE_MSG_ANY
Wildcard for filtering (15).
.SS Message Tag Constants
.TP
.B HIVE_TAG_NONE
No tag (0).
.TP
.B HIVE_TAG_ANY
Wildcard for filtering in
.BR hive_ipc_recv_match ().
.SS Special Sender IDs
.TP
.B HIVE_SENDER_ANY
Wildcard for filtering in
.BR hive_ipc_recv_match ()
(0xFFFFFFFF).
.PP
.B Note:
Timer messages have the owning actor as sender. Exit notifications have the
dying actor as sender. Use message class to identify system messages.
.SS Timeout Constants
.TP
.B HIVE_TIMEOUT_INFINITE (-1)
Block forever until operation completes.
.TP
.B HIVE_TIMEOUT_NONBLOCKING (0)
Return immediately if operation would block.
.SS Priority Levels
.TP
.B HIVE_PRIORITY_CRITICAL (0)
Highest priority. Safety-critical tasks: flight control, emergency stop.
.TP
.B HIVE_PRIORITY_HIGH (1)
Time-sensitive tasks: sensor fusion, control loops.
.TP
.B HIVE_PRIORITY_NORMAL (2)
Standard tasks: telemetry, logging. Default priority.
.TP
.B HIVE_PRIORITY_LOW (3)
Background tasks: diagnostics, housekeeping.
.PP
Lower numeric value means higher priority. Higher priority actors always run
before lower priority actors.
.SS Actor Configuration
.PP
.nf
typedef struct {
    size_t      stack_size;   /* bytes, 0 = default (64KB) */
    hive_priority_level priority;
    const char *name;         /* for debugging, may be NULL */
    bool        malloc_stack; /* false = arena (default), true = malloc */
} actor_config;

#define HIVE_ACTOR_CONFIG_DEFAULT { \\
    .stack_size = 0, \\
    .priority = HIVE_PRIORITY_NORMAL, \\
    .name = NULL, \\
    .malloc_stack = false \\
}
.fi
.SS Exit Reasons
.TP
.B HIVE_EXIT_NORMAL
Actor called
.BR hive_exit ().
.TP
.B HIVE_EXIT_CRASH
Actor function returned without calling
.BR hive_exit ().
.TP
.B HIVE_EXIT_CRASH_STACK
Stack overflow detected (reserved for future hardware-based detection).
.TP
.B HIVE_EXIT_KILLED
Actor was killed externally (reserved for future use).
.SS Exit Message Payload
.PP
Defined in
.IR <hive_link.h> :
.PP
.nf
typedef struct {
    actor_id       actor;   /* ID of the actor that died */
    hive_exit_reason reason;  /* Why the actor exited */
} hive_exit_msg;
.fi
.PP
Use helper functions from
.BR hive_link (3):
.BR hive_is_exit_msg ()
and
.BR hive_decode_exit ().
.SH COMPILE-TIME CONFIGURATION
All resource limits are defined in
.I hive_static_config.h
and can be overridden with
.B -D
compiler flags. Changing these values requires recompilation.
.SS Feature Toggles
.TP
.B HIVE_ENABLE_NET (1)
Enable network I/O subsystem. Set to 0 to disable.
.TP
.B HIVE_ENABLE_FILE (1)
Enable file I/O subsystem. Set to 0 to disable.
.PP
Can also be set via Makefile:
.I make ENABLE_NET=0 ENABLE_FILE=0
.SS Actor Configuration
.TP
.B HIVE_MAX_ACTORS (64)
Maximum concurrent actors.
.TP
.B HIVE_DEFAULT_STACK_SIZE (65536)
Default stack size per actor in bytes (64 KB).
.TP
.B HIVE_STACK_ARENA_SIZE (1048576)
Total stack arena size in bytes (1 MB). Actors with
.I malloc_stack = false
allocate from this arena.
.SS IPC Configuration
.TP
.B HIVE_MAILBOX_ENTRY_POOL_SIZE (256)
Global pool of mailbox entries. Each pending message consumes one entry.
.TP
.B HIVE_MESSAGE_DATA_POOL_SIZE (256)
Global pool of message data buffers.
.TP
.B HIVE_MAX_MESSAGE_SIZE (256)
Maximum message size in bytes (includes 4-byte header, so 252 bytes payload).
.SS Link/Monitor Configuration
.TP
.B HIVE_LINK_ENTRY_POOL_SIZE (128)
Pool for bidirectional links. Each
.BR hive_link ()
consumes two entries.
.TP
.B HIVE_MONITOR_ENTRY_POOL_SIZE (128)
Pool for unidirectional monitors. Each
.BR hive_monitor ()
consumes one entry.
.SS Timer Configuration
.TP
.B HIVE_TIMER_ENTRY_POOL_SIZE (64)
Pool for timers. Each active timer consumes one entry.
.SS Bus Configuration
.TP
.B HIVE_MAX_BUSES (32)
Maximum concurrent buses.
.TP
.B HIVE_MAX_BUS_ENTRIES (64)
Maximum entries per bus ring buffer.
.TP
.B HIVE_MAX_BUS_SUBSCRIBERS (32)
Maximum subscribers per bus.
.SS Supervisor Configuration
.TP
.B HIVE_MAX_SUPERVISORS (8)
Maximum concurrent supervisors.
.TP
.B HIVE_MAX_SUPERVISOR_CHILDREN (16)
Maximum children per supervisor.
.SS Name Registry Configuration
.TP
.B HIVE_MAX_REGISTERED_NAMES (32)
Maximum registered actor names. Used by
.BR hive_register (),
.BR hive_whereis (),
and
.BR hive_unregister ().
.SS Scheduler Configuration
.TP
.B HIVE_EPOLL_MAX_EVENTS (64)
Maximum epoll events processed per scheduler iteration.
.TP
.B HIVE_EPOLL_POLL_TIMEOUT_MS (10)
Epoll poll timeout in milliseconds (defensive wakeup interval).
.SS Network Configuration
.TP
.B HIVE_NET_LISTEN_BACKLOG (5)
TCP listen backlog (queued connections).
.SH MEMORY FOOTPRINT
With default configuration, static memory footprint is approximately:
.PP
.nf
Stack arena:          1,048,576 bytes (1 MB)
Actor table:             ~8,000 bytes
Mailbox pool:           ~16,000 bytes
Message pool:           ~65,000 bytes
Link/Monitor pools:      ~4,000 bytes
Timer pool:              ~2,000 bytes
Bus structures:         ~40,000 bytes
-----------------------------------
Total:               ~1.2 MB static
.fi
.PP
Additional memory if
.I malloc_stack = true
is used for some actors.
.SH NOTES
.SS Deterministic Memory
All runtime structures are statically allocated at compile time. No heap
allocation occurs in hot paths (IPC, scheduling, I/O). This enables:
.IP \(bu 2
Calculable memory footprint at link time
.IP \(bu 2
Zero heap fragmentation
.IP \(bu 2
Certification for safety-critical systems
.SS Error Message Lifetime
The
.I msg
field in
.I hive_status
is always a string literal, never heap-allocated. It remains valid indefinitely.
.SS Message Data Lifetime
The
.I data
field in
.I hive_message
points to a shared buffer that is overwritten on the next successful
.BR hive_ipc_recv ().
Copy data immediately if needed later.
.SH EXAMPLE
.SS Error Handling Pattern
.nf
hive_status s = hive_spawn(my_fn, NULL, &id);
if (HIVE_FAILED(s)) {
    printf("Spawn failed: %s\\n", HIVE_ERR_STR(s));
    return -1;
}
.fi
.SS Custom Configuration
.nf
/* Build with custom limits */
gcc -DHIVE_MAX_ACTORS=128 \\
    -DHIVE_MAX_MESSAGE_SIZE=512 \\
    -DHIVE_STACK_ARENA_SIZE=2097152 \\
    -o myapp myapp.c -lhive
.fi
